TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Dynamics of Action-Oriented Problem Solving: Linking Interpretation and Choice
AU  - Rudolph, Jenny W.
AU  - Morrison, J. Bradley
AU  - Carroll, John S.
Y1  - 2009/10/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.34.4.zok733
DO  - 10.5465/amr.34.4.zok733
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 733
EP  - 756
VL  - 34
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We offer a theory of action-oriented problem solving that links interpretation and choice, processes usually separated in the sensemaking literature and decision-making literature. Through an iterative, simulation-based process we developed a formal model. Three insights emerged: (1) action-oriented problem solving includes acting, interpreting, and cultivating diagnoses; (2) feedback among these processes opens and closes windows of adaptive problem solving; and (3) reinforcing feedback and confirmation bias, usually considered dysfunctional, are helpful for adaptive problem solving.
AB  - We offer a theory of action-oriented problem solving that links interpretation and choice, processes usually separated in the sensemaking literature and decision-making literature. Through an iterative, simulation-based process we developed a formal model. Three insights emerged: (1) action-oriented problem solving includes acting, interpreting, and cultivating diagnoses; (2) feedback among these processes opens and closes windows of adaptive problem solving; and (3) reinforcing feedback and confirmation bias, usually considered dysfunctional, are helpful for adaptive problem solving.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.34.4.zok733
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.34.4.zok733
Y2  - 2026/04/24
