TY  - JOUR
T1  - Selectivity in Organizational Rule Violations
AU  - Lehman, David W.
AU  - Ramanujam, Rangaraj
Y1  - 2009/10/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.34.4.zok643
DO  - 10.5465/amr.34.4.zok643
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 643
EP  - 657
VL  - 34
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Organizational rule violations are more likely when performance falls below aspiration levels. We propose that such violations are systematically selective and that this selectivity emerges during the problemistic search for solutions to the performance shortfall. During this search, contextual conditions (structural secrecy and coupling between violations and outcomes) and characteristics of rules (enforceability, procedural emphasis, and connectedness) direct attention and shape risk perceptions. Consequently, some rules are more likely to be violated than others.
AB  - Organizational rule violations are more likely when performance falls below aspiration levels. We propose that such violations are systematically selective and that this selectivity emerges during the problemistic search for solutions to the performance shortfall. During this search, contextual conditions (structural secrecy and coupling between violations and outcomes) and characteristics of rules (enforceability, procedural emphasis, and connectedness) direct attention and shape risk perceptions. Consequently, some rules are more likely to be violated than others.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.34.4.zok643
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.34.4.zok643
